WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.760
Continuing our discussion of all the different components, concepts, constructs and models

00:19.760 --> 00:34.400
that we have.

00:34.400 --> 00:39.920
Continuing our discussion of all the different components, concepts, constructs and models that

00:39.920 --> 00:45.480
we have within computer systems, let's now talk about the concept of the ring protection

00:45.480 --> 00:46.800
model.

00:46.800 --> 00:48.720
So here's the idea behind this.

00:48.720 --> 00:53.760
Within any modern computing system, we have all sorts of different layers of software.

00:53.760 --> 00:56.760
At the heart of the system, we have the system kernel.

00:56.760 --> 00:59.080
This is the core of the operating system.

00:59.080 --> 01:03.600
That system kernel kernel is going to connect to different drivers and libraries to create

01:03.600 --> 01:05.080
the operating system.

01:05.080 --> 01:07.720
And on top of that, you're going to be running programs.

01:07.720 --> 01:12.320
And the idea behind the ring protection model is to assign these different essentially

01:12.320 --> 01:18.080
layers, these rings of hardware, different levels of trust.

01:18.080 --> 01:23.080
And the idea being the more valuable, the more trust that's required for one of the rings,

01:23.080 --> 01:26.080
the more controls, protection mechanisms you're going to want to have.

01:26.080 --> 01:30.840
And as you radiate outwards to less and less trusted, less and less value pieces of the

01:30.840 --> 01:33.600
system, you're going to have less controls in place.

01:33.600 --> 01:36.160
That's the idea behind the ring protection model.

01:36.160 --> 01:42.400
Now ring zero, the center, is always known as where the system kernel runs.

01:42.400 --> 01:46.920
So you will call the system kernel as the core, the heart of an operating system.

01:46.920 --> 01:49.680
And this is the most important piece of software on a system.

01:49.680 --> 01:52.080
It's what controls access to everything.

01:52.080 --> 01:55.920
It's what controls everything, essentially, it's the most important part.

01:55.920 --> 01:57.520
So it runs at ring zero.

01:57.520 --> 02:01.400
And this is obviously where we're going to have the greatest level of trust, the most

02:01.400 --> 02:06.400
controls in place to protect this very valuable and important system kernel.

02:06.400 --> 02:10.680
Now the next two rings, ring one and ring two, don't worry about what they cover, what

02:10.680 --> 02:11.680
they do.

02:11.680 --> 02:15.240
The reason I'm telling you that is that in the industry, if you look at Windows Unix,

02:15.240 --> 02:20.400
Linux, Mac, there's no consistency on what these two rings are used for.

02:20.400 --> 02:22.040
So you won't get questions on the exam.

02:22.040 --> 02:26.240
You might be asked what's at ring zero to which you will answer the system kernel.

02:26.240 --> 02:30.320
And you might get questions about ring three, because ring three is always where your

02:30.320 --> 02:32.800
user programs run.

02:32.800 --> 02:34.400
So this is the idea of the ring protection model.

02:34.400 --> 02:38.600
You rate eight outwards at the center, ring zero is where you have the most trust.

02:38.600 --> 02:45.320
And you rate eight outwards to layer three, ring three where you have the least trust.

02:45.320 --> 02:49.880
Next, let's talk about the concept of secure memory management.

02:49.880 --> 02:54.560
And this is the idea that in a system, we'll have multiple programs running.

02:54.560 --> 02:59.640
And each of those programs will have some data loaded into volatile memory, RAM, random

02:59.640 --> 03:01.600
access memory.

03:01.600 --> 03:05.960
And the idea behind secure memory management is that we want to make sure that if, if

03:05.960 --> 03:11.280
process A is accessing data in RAM, what data should be allowed to access?

03:11.280 --> 03:12.280
Only its own data.

03:12.280 --> 03:14.160
That's the idea of secure memory management.

03:14.160 --> 03:17.760
You allocate parts of memory to different processes.

03:17.760 --> 03:22.000
And then you have a component in place system that's controlling and making sure that only

03:22.000 --> 03:26.240
process A can access process A's data in memory.

03:26.240 --> 03:31.240
What do you think we would fundamentally call that system that's mediating that access?

03:31.240 --> 03:33.040
That would be a security kernel.

03:33.040 --> 03:37.840
So secure memory management is about essentially implementing a security kernel that controls

03:37.840 --> 03:40.800
which processes can access, which data in RAM.

03:40.800 --> 03:45.760
And as you can see here in the diagram, process A can only access process A's data and not

03:45.760 --> 03:50.600
data from the operating system or other processes.

03:50.600 --> 03:53.040
Next we have the concept of data hiding.

03:53.040 --> 03:59.360
And this is the idea that we can have data at different levels of confidentiality or value.

03:59.360 --> 04:04.280
And the idea behind data hiding is that if you are at a lower level of confidentiality,

04:04.280 --> 04:06.840
then you cannot see data at higher levels.

04:06.840 --> 04:09.280
That data is hidden from you.

04:09.280 --> 04:14.680
And so data hiding is basically just an implementation of which model that John talked about.

04:14.680 --> 04:19.680
Which model had to do with confidential data at different layers?

04:20.680 --> 04:24.200
And so Bella Padula is essentially what data hiding is all about.

04:24.200 --> 04:30.520
If you're down at a lower level of secrecy, you can't see data at higher levels of secrecy.

04:30.520 --> 04:35.080
The last piece we'll talk about in this section is what is known as code signing and validation.

04:35.080 --> 04:39.120
And this actually relies on a lot of cryptographic technologies and techniques that we haven't

04:39.120 --> 04:42.200
talked about yet like hashing and digital signatures and so forth.

04:42.200 --> 04:45.640
So don't worry about the technical pieces of how this actually works.

04:45.640 --> 04:48.640
Just understand what we use code signing and validation for.

04:48.640 --> 04:52.800
And later on, we'll explain how this actually gets done.

04:52.800 --> 04:55.200
So here's what you use code signing and validation for.

04:55.200 --> 04:59.080
And let me use a modern phone, something like an iPhone as an example.

04:59.080 --> 05:01.320
So we've all got phones, something like this.

05:01.320 --> 05:05.520
And you probably notice that every so often you get a little nudge from Apple saying,

05:05.520 --> 05:07.000
hey, you need to update your device.

05:07.000 --> 05:12.240
Hey, hey, and what you're going to go and do is you're going to go into system settings

05:12.240 --> 05:14.920
and you're going to say, update my device.

05:14.920 --> 05:17.560
And when you've done this, you probably notice that when you say, you know,

05:17.560 --> 05:20.520
you finally go through all the, you know, all the click wrap agreements and accept all

05:20.520 --> 05:23.720
the terms and conditions and everything and you finally say, yeah, install the update.

05:23.720 --> 05:28.320
It doesn't just install instantly for the first little while it says downloading.

05:28.320 --> 05:32.440
But then when it's done downloading, it doesn't again just install instantly instead.

05:32.440 --> 05:33.440
What does it say?

05:33.440 --> 05:36.280
So if it took like 10 minutes to download, then usually for like the next 10 minutes,

05:36.280 --> 05:37.760
what does it say?

05:37.760 --> 05:38.760
Verifying.

05:38.760 --> 05:43.640
Now, there's something really cool happening behind the scenes when it says verifying.

05:43.640 --> 05:46.920
What your phone is actually doing is it's making sure that that software update that it

05:46.920 --> 05:52.520
just downloaded actually came from Apple because if you're downloading an update to your

05:52.520 --> 05:55.440
phone that's going to make a whole bunch of changes to your operating system, you want

05:55.440 --> 05:58.000
to make darn sure that actually came from a trusted source.

05:58.000 --> 06:01.560
And so if it's an Apple phone, you want to make sure it came from Apple.

06:01.560 --> 06:05.560
So the first thing that code signing validation is all about is the authenticity.

06:05.560 --> 06:08.800
You know who the update came from.

06:08.800 --> 06:11.560
And the next piece is integrity.

06:11.560 --> 06:16.440
If you've downloaded all this code from Apple, you want to make sure that none of the instructions

06:16.440 --> 06:19.080
have gotten scrambled, none of the pieces are missing.

06:19.080 --> 06:24.800
You want to make sure that that whole software update is complete, has integrity.

06:24.800 --> 06:29.840
And so that's the two major pieces of functionality that code signing provides.

06:29.840 --> 06:33.360
It allows you to know where a software update came from.

06:33.360 --> 06:38.480
And make sure that that software update has integrity, so authenticity and integrity.

06:38.480 --> 06:42.400
And the way that we achieve this is by creating what are known as digital signatures.

06:42.400 --> 06:45.320
And here's the stuff that we'll talk about in a lot more detail in the cryptographic

06:45.320 --> 06:46.720
section, section.

06:46.720 --> 06:52.880
But you take your code, you hash that code, producing a fixed linked message digest, the

06:52.880 --> 06:58.000
author of the software, then encrypts that digest with their private key, creating what

06:58.000 --> 07:00.640
is known as a digital signature.

07:00.640 --> 07:03.840
That's how you sign code, you create a digital signature.

07:03.840 --> 07:06.640
So that's the idea behind code signing.

